About this time, the great question arose, regard- ing the validity of baptism when given by heretics. S. Cyprian being first consulted, pronounced it to be no baptism, unless it is given in the communion of the Church. And therefore all heretice who are re- conciled ought, as be said, to be baptized. As an authority for his opinion, he cited the practice of his predecessor Agrippinus. He was supported by Dio- nysius of Alexandria, and by a synod of thirty-two African bishops.
